The paper focuses on modeling the dynamic information diffusion process in social networks using an evolutionary game theoretic framework. This involves analyzing network users' decisions, actions, and socio-economic connections, which falls under the categories of social networks (cs.SOC), game theory (cs.GT), and data science (cs.DS). Additionally, the paper discusses the network structure modeling of Erdos-Renyi random network and the Barabasi-Albert scale-free network, which falls under the category of computational complexity (cs.CY). Finally, the paper uses experiments with real-world Facebook network and information spreading dataset of Memetracker, which falls under the category of social computing (cs.SI).
